{"type":"message","id":"a7981c32","parentId":"f224296e","timestamp":"2026-03-22T00:12:05.000Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to handle the `/hold1`, `/hold2`, etc. commands. When I receive a message that starts with `/hold`, I should:\n1. Parse which hold number it is\n2. Save the current topic/conversation context to that hold\n3. Acknowledge it\n\nBut wait - I need to know what the \"current topic\" is. Looking at the conversation, the last meaningful message before the `/hold` command would be what we save. Actually, I think the user wants to save the current working topic - so when they say `/hold1`, I should save a description of what we were just talking about.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The workflow would be:\n1. User says \"let's put this aside\" → types `/hold1`\n2. I save the current topic/together with context to hold slot 1\n3. Later user can say `/holds` to see all holds, or `/hold1` to resume\n\nThe tricky part is knowing what \"the current topic\" is. In a conversation, the topic before the `/hold1` command is the last substantial message. But I should probably ask the user to confirm what to save, OR just save a summary of what we were discussing.\n\nActually, looking at the conversation flow - right now we're in the middle of building the causal-minimal project. So if Zach says `/hold1`, I'd save \"causal-minimal project - state encoder + grid world + causal graph + synthesis\".\n\nLet me implement a simple system where:\n- `/hold[N]` → saves current topic to slot N (I'll infer from recent context)\n- `/holds` → shows all current holds\n- `/clearhold[N]` → clears slot N\n\nI'll parse the command, extract the number, and manage the holds.md file.","thinkingSignature":"5661f1b7c3737bd2e65a9e92ee0a8c9fd85b358ba584ea41ee83219f377c9627"},{"type":"text","text":"Now I'll handle `/hold1`, `/hold2`, `/holds`, and `/clearhold` commands. When you use `/hold1`, I'll grab the last topic we were di