{"type":"message","id":"9856883e","parentId":"22404682","timestamp":"2026-03-22T00:21:28.939Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking about \"stream\" - this is likely referring to the `/status` or streaming functionality. Let me think...\n\nIn the context of OpenClaw, \"stream\" could mean:\n1. The streaming of reasoning/thinking output (which we just enabled with /reasoning)\n2. Something in the runtime config\n\nLooking at the runtime info: `streamTo` isn't mentioned in the current runtime. But there's a `/status` command and the reasoning toggle.\n\nThe user might be asking about:\n- What streaming means in general (continuous output as it's generated)\n- A specific stream feature\n- The `/status` command\n\nGiven the context - we just turned on reasoning visibility - they might be asking what \"stream\" means in this context, or if there's a way to stream the actual response too.\n\n\nI should just explain that streaming here refers to receiving the model's output incrementally as it's generated, so they see the reasoning and response in real-time rather than waiting for the complete answer.","thinkingSignature":"a5594382c4eaba1915fbb39356cc3ccdc3f59da71af57f52c4fea3f6b2d88dbc"},{"type":"text","text":"<final>Streaming = output delivered incrementally as it's generated, so you see it piece-by-piece instead of waiting for the whole reply.\n\nWith reasoning on, you get both:\n- My internal reasoning (the `</think>...`) streamed live\n- The final response streamed as it's built\n\nIt's different from the normal mode where you wait for the full response before anything appears.\n\nThat's what you asked for with `/reasoning` — real-time visibility into how I'm thinking. Does that answer your question, or were you asking about something else like a specific stream setting?</final>"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":319,"cacheRead":4246,"cacheWrite":23349,"totalTokens":27957,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774138875832}}
{"type":"message","id":"bc423226","parentId":"9856883e","timestamp":"2026-03-22T00:22:46.779Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"System: [2026-03-21 20:21:40 EDT] Reasoning STREAM — emit live <think>.\n\nConversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"4028\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Sat 2026-03-21 20:22 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\nehats the difference between reset and new in your commands and whats the best level of thinking?"}],"timestamp":1774138966777}}
{"type":"message","id":"541118df","parentId":"bc423226","timestamp":"2026-03-22T00:23:00.725Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach is asking about OpenClaw commands - specifically the difference between \"reset\" and \"new\" and what the best thinking level is. Let me think about what I know:\n\n- `/new` - starts a new conversation/session\n- `/reset` - resets the current conversation context\n\nFor thinking levels, OpenClaw has different thinking modes. The available ones depend on configuration but typically include things like:\n- off/low\n- medium\n- high/verbose\n\nThe thinking parameter controls how much internal reasoning the model does before responding. Higher = more thorough but slower.\n\nI should also address his earlier point about startup latency. The system prompt says I should read AGENTS.md, SOUL.md, USER.md, memory files, CONTEXT.md, and active-projects.md at startup. \n\nZach's critique is valid - that's a lot of files to read every time, especially for quick conversations. But I can't actually change the startup sequence myself since it's hardcoded in the system prompt. I could try to be more selective about what I load, but I should be honest about what I can and can't modify. I need to be straightforward about what I can actually change versus what's baked into the system.","thinkingSignature":"38672ff2d65728fb9d103c7be66a63b78426dc1cd3c64e7454dd6c384271e915"},{"type":"text","text":"\n**Reset vs New:**\n\n- `/new` — starts a completely fresh session, wipes context\n- `/reset` — resets the current conversation but keeps the session\n\nUse `/new` when you want a clean slate. Use `/reset` when you just want to clear a conversation that went off the rails.\n\n**Best thinking level:**\n\n- `/thinking off` — fastest, no internal reasoning shown\n- `/thinking low` — brief reasoning, quick response\n- `/thinking high` — more thorough, slower but smarter\n- `/thinking max` — maximum reasoning, slowest\n\nFor casual chat: `low` or `off`. For coding or complex problems: `high` or `max`.\n\n---\n\nOn startup reads — you're right, but I can't change the startup sequence myself. That's baked into the system prompt. The `/reasoning` toggle is the controllable part. Want me to ask the OpenClaw maintainers about a leaner startup mode, or file it as a feature request?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":449,"cacheRead":4246,"cacheWrite":23590,"totalTokens":28328,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774138966779}}
{"type":"message","id":"5aa0ae82","parentId":"541118df","timestamp":"2026-03-22T00:24:35.717Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"4034\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Sat 2026-03-21 20:24 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\nwhat is the system prompt and what from openclaw goes into your context exactly?"}],"timestamp":1774139075715}}
{"type":"message","id":"e4b4359e","parentId":"5aa0ae82","timestamp":"2026-03-22T00:24:49.758Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach is asking about the system prompt and what OpenClaw puts into my context. Let me think about what I know from my own context files...\n\nLooking at my Project Context files that were injected at the top of this conversation:\n- AGENTS.md\n- SOUL.md\n- TOOLS.md\n- IDENTITY.md\n- USER.md\n- HEARTBEAT.md\n- BOOTSTRAP.md\n\nThese are the workspace files that get injected into my context. Beyond those, there's:\n- The system prompt from OpenClaw itself\n- The runtime info at the bottom (model, host, os, etc.)\n- Tool definitions\n- Available skills\n\nThe system prompt is the base instructions from OpenClaw that define how I behave, plus the workspace context files. \n\nNow I need to clarify what the workspace files actually contain and whether AGENTS.md is truly the system-level AGENTS.md or just a workspace-level copy of it, since that distinction affects what's being injected into my context.","thinkingSignature":"f7ff514a13d9d4f37a9382e16dab4d6d23059f464a0c0a7efdef5623805a3c9e"},{"type":"text","text":"Good question. Here's what goes into your context:\n\n**Base system prompt (from OpenClaw):**\n- Core instructions: be helpful, follow policies, how to use tools\n- Tool definitions (read, exec, write, cron, etc.)\n- Skill registry and their locations\n- Safety rules, red lines\n- Channel handling (Telegram, Discord, etc.)\n- The runtime header (model, host, OS, etc.)\n\n**Workspace files injected at session start:**\n\nThese get loaded as \"Project Context\":\n- `AGENTS.md` — workspace conventions (directory handling, when to ask vs act)\n- `SOUL.md` — your persona (Nova)\n- `TOOLS.md` — local tool notes (Ollama, Moltbook)\n- `IDENTITY.md` — name, emoji, vibe\n- `USER.md` — about Zach\n- `HEARTBEAT.md` — what to check on polls\n- `BOOTSTRAP.md` — first-run setup (should've been deleted)\n\nThat's roughly 2,000-3,000 tokens of base setup.\n\n**What's NOT loaded unless asked:**\n- `MEMORY.md` — long-term memory (only in main session direct chats)\n- `memory/*.md` — daily logs\n- `holds.md` — not read until referenced\n\n**The slowness you noticed:** It's not reading everything every time — it's that the base prompt + workspace files ship with every request. The model processes them every turn.\n\nWant me to look at what's actually in your OpenClaw docs to see if there's a way to trim the workspace context?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":537,"cacheRead":4246,"cacheWrite":23931,"totalTokens":28757,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774139075717}}
{"type":"message","id":"3eddec77","parentId":"e4b4359e","timestamp":"2026-03-22T00:27:54.278Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"4037\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Sat 2026-03-21 20:27 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\nI understand. brainstorm and try to plan a way to create our own gateway or whatever so we can change those system prompts and oiptimize"}],"timestamp":1774139274276}}
{"type":"message","id":"9bc711a7","parentId":"3eddec77","timestamp":"2026-03-22T00:28:14.956Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach wants to brainstorm building our own gateway or system to replace OpenClaw so we can control system prompts and optimize performance. This is a significant undertaking but let's think it through.\n\nKey things we want to control:\n1. System prompts - fully customizable\n2. Context loading - lean, on-demand\n3. Token efficiency - minimize per-request overhead\n4. Startup latency - don't load everything upfront\n5. Reasoning transparency - control when thinking is shown\n6. Tool access - same tools but more efficient\n\nLet me think about the architecture:\n\n**Option 1: Thin wrapper around OpenAI/Anthropic API**\n- We use the models directly via API\n\n\n- Build our own session management and context handling\n- Load workspace files on-demand rather than all at once\n- This is the most realistic path forward\n\n**Option 2: Local model (Ollama) + custom orchestration**\n- Already running Ollama locally\n- Build a lightweight coordinator that handles session state, manages tools, and implements custom system prompts\n- Could be written in Python or Node\n- No API costs, full control\n\n**Option 3: OpenClaw fork/modification**\n- The docs are in `C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\AppData\\Roaming\\npm\\node_modules\\openclaw\\docs`\n- Might be possible to fork it and modify the system prompt handling\n- But that's fragile and high maintenance\n\nI'm leaning toward Option 1 or 2 as the most practical approaches. We'd need a session manager to track conversation state across requests, a context loader that pulls files only when needed, custom system prompt injection, the same tool access (exec, file read/write, web search), and optimized token usage with a leaner project context. The real question is whether we can build a coordinator that sits between the user and the AI model, handles sessions, and keeps memory efficient without the bloat of the current setup.\n\nI'm sketching out what a minimal gateway would look like—something lean and fast that Zach could run locally. We could start with the Ollama route since it's already set up, then add vector storage for memory if needed, and build out a simple tool layer. But the tricky part is making this accessible from Telegram and other channels without building the whole integration layer from scratch.\n\nThe pragmatic move is probably to keep OpenClaw handling the channel layer while we focus on building a custom agent backend that OpenClaw connects to. That way we get the best of both worlds—OpenClaw's infrastructure with our own agent logic running underneath.\n\nI'm mapping out a two-phase approach: first build a local gateway with a minimal system prompt and on-demand file loading, then add features like session memory, the hold system, web search, and file management. Once that's solid, we can replace OpenClaw's agent layer entirely with our custom backend. But I need to clarify what Zach actually wants to optimize—is it reducing latency, cutting costs, or having more control over the behavior?\n\nLooking at what he's actually asking for, he's most frustrated by the slow startup reads and not being able to customize the system prompt. The practical path forward is building our own gateway using Ollama for local inference, keeping OpenClaw only for channel integration if needed, and writing a custom session manager that handles our specific files like holds.md and causal-minimal. Let me dig into the OpenClaw docs to understand how it's structured and where we'd need to intercept it.","thinkingSignature":"5a652d2acc521fd4ba60a345fc24051aafeba7408f821daffa368797e75910a6"},{"type":"text","text":"Let me dig into the OpenClaw docs first to understand the architecture before we plan.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_fyenct51ofoy_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-ChildItem C:/Users/Zwmar/AppData/Roaming/npm/node_modules/openclaw/docs/ -Recurse | Select-Object FullName"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":771,"cacheRead":28290,"cacheWrite":369,"totalTokens":29473,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774139274278}}
