{"type":"message","id":"ec5620be","parentId":"2967c670","timestamp":"2026-03-22T00:29:02.039Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a solid picture. Let me think about the architecture options:\n\n**What we learned:**\n1. OpenClaw has `agents.defaults.bootstrapMaxChars`, `bootstrapTotalMaxChars` — we can control file sizes\n2. There's a `lightContext` option for heartbeat runs (only HEARTBEAT.md)\n3. There's a `promptMode: minimal` for sub-agents that omits a lot of sections\n4. Bootstrap files are injected on every turn — they're not just read once at startup\n5. Tool schemas are JSON and count toward context significantly\n6. OpenClaw uses WebSocket gateway architecture\n\n\n7. The gateway owns messaging surfaces while clients connect via WebSocket to send requests\n\nThe real bottleneck isn't startup reads — it's the cumulative cost of bootstrap files, tool schemas, and conversation history across every single turn. For optimization, I should focus on trimming bootstrap file sizes, leveraging the minimal prompt mode where possible, and potentially replacing the agent layer entirely with our own implementation if we want full control over the system prompt and context assembly.\n\nFor a custom gateway, the architecture would layer as follows: an API gateway handling channel connections (Telegram, etc.), a session manager tracking conversation state and history, a context assembler building prompts from bootstrap files and tool schemas, an agent engine running the actual model, and tool services. The fastest path to customization without rebuilding everything from scratch would be modifying bootstrap files to be ultra-lean, using the minimal prompt mode for most interactions, and potentially building a separate custom agent backend that the gateway routes to. Since Ollama is already running locally, that could serve as the inference engine.\n\nBut Zach's vision goes further—he wants complete system prompt control, a lean on-demand context system, reasoning transparency, minimal latency, custom commands, and full ownership of the data. So the real question becomes whether to build our own agent from scratch using Ollama, create a minimal context assembly layer, implement a command system, and integrate with Telegram and other channels.\n\nThe practical path forward is building Nova as a lightweight Python gateway that wraps Ollama for inference, manages sessions and context assembly, handles tool execution, and connects to Telegram. The gateway would own channel integration while our custom agent layer handles the intelligence—staying lean by only loading context when needed rather than pre-loading everything.\n\nFor the architecture, I'm thinking session state stays in memory or simple JSON files, context gets assembled per request from minimal bootstrap files and conversation history, the system prompt gets built from a template we fully control, and we use Ollama for inference with tool results fed back in. The key insight is keeping bootstrap files to 50 lines max and loading everything else on-demand rather than at startup.\n\nLooking at the actual constraints: the 26k token context usage is reasonable for a 200k window, so compaction failures might stem from file bloat. The real optimization isn't cutting startup reads—it's keeping bootstrap files lean and only loading history when necessary.\n\nMy approach would be to first trim the workspace files down significantly, then explore a local Ollama gateway if we need deeper customization.","thinkingSignature":"a01b38c15b039d5fd30e125ee357cf7c507c7e75b87c5b1b4fab2cf3d856c629"},{"type":"text","text":"\nGood data. Here's the picture:\n\n**What we learned:**\n- Bootstrap files are injected **every turn**, not just at startup — that's the real token burn\n- `TOOLS.md` is 54KB raw → 21KB injected (biggest offender)\n- Tool schemas (JSON) also count toward context each turn\n- `lightContext: true` already exists for heartbeat runs (only loads HEARTBEAT.md)\n- There's a `promptMode: minimal` for sub-agents that strips Skills, Memory, Heartbeats, etc.\n\n**The path forward — two options:**\n\n### Option A: Quick wins (right now)\n1. Trim `TOOLS.md` drastically — it's carrying weight we don't need every turn\n2. Set `bootstrapTotalMaxChars: 30000` to hard-cap injection\n3. Use `lightContext: true` globally (not just heartbeats)\n4. Keep OpenClaw, just control what it injects\n\n### Option B: Build our own gateway (real project)\nA lean Python/Node process that:\n- Wraps Ollama (already running locally)\n- Owns session state + context assembly\n- Fully custom system prompt we write\n- On-demand file loading only\n- Hooks into Telegram via bot API directly\n\n**Option B is the real answer to \"control system prompts\"** — we replace the agent loop entirely. OpenClaw handles the channel transport; we handle everything else.\n\nWant me to spec out Option B? This is a real project — could be the most impactful thing we build."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":49270,"output":949,"cacheRead":12389,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":62608,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774139314512}}
{"type":"message","id":"822496ab","parentId":"ec5620be","timestamp":"2026-03-22T00:31:18.779Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"4044\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"sender\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Sat 2026-03-21 20:31 EDT\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"Ton0Fun (8371302588)\",\n  \"id\": \"8371302588\",\n  \"name\": \"Ton0Fun\",\n  \"username\": \"Ton0Fun\"\n}\n```\n\nwhat is a good size model to run that will match the quality of an api call"}],"timestamp":1774139478777}}
{"type":"message","id":"d584a2c4","parentId":"822496ab","timestamp":"2026-03-22T00:31:42.949Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking about local LLM models that can match API quality. This is a practical question about Ollama model selection. Let me think about this:\n\nFor local models via Ollama that can match API (OpenAI/Anthropic) quality:\n- **Qwen2.5 14B** — strong reasoning, good code, efficient\n- **Qwen2.5 32B** — even better, still fits on decent GPU\n- **Llama3.3 70B** — top tier open weights, needs good VRAM\n- **Mistral Small** — 22B, surprisingly good\n- **DeepSeek V3** — 671B parameters (but with MoE, only ~37B active) — excellent reasoning\n\n\n- **Command R7B** — compact but surprisingly capable\n\nI need to understand their hardware setup first since Ollama performance depends heavily on available VRAM and memory. For comparison, MiniMax M2.5 API sits somewhere between GPT-4o mini and GPT-4o in capability, so they're looking for something in that range locally.\n\nGiven the tech stack constraints—Windows with an RTX 3060, 12GB VRAM—my best recommendations would be Qwen2.5 14B for a good balance of quality and speed, DeepSeek V3 7B for pure speed, or Qwen2.5 32B if they have more VRAM available. The 3060's 12GB limits what can run at full capacity, though Qwen2.5 14B should work reasonably well within those constraints.","thinkingSignature":"55f509e1a4a4209f8bdf8d516c9759704527ce30f025c1a4527853250b52d991"},{"type":"text","text":"Depends on your hardware, but here's the practical range:\n\n**For RTX 3060 (12GB VRAM) — what actually fits and performs:**\n\n| Model | Size | Quality | Speed |\n|-------|------|---------|-------|\n| **Qwen2.5 14B** | ~8GB VRAM | Closest to API quality | ~15-20 tok/s |\n| **DeepSeek V3 7B** | ~4GB VRAM | Shocking good for size | ~25-30 tok/s |\n| **Qwen2.5 7B** | ~4GB VRAM | Solid fast option | ~30 tok/s |\n| **Llama3.2 3B** | ~2GB VRAM | Usable, not great | ~40 tok/s |\n\n**If you have more VRAM (4090, A100, etc.):**\n- **Qwen2.5 32B** — actually rivals GPT-4o level\n- **DeepSeek V3 671B MoE** — best open-weights reasoning, ~37B active\n- **Llama3.3 70B** — top tier but needs 40GB+\n\n**My recommendation for your setup:**\n`qwen2.5:14b` — it's the sweet spot for 3060. Quality is close enough to not frustrate you, and it actually fits in memory without constant swapping.\n\nTo pull it:\n```\nollama pull qwen2.5:14b\n```\n\nWhat's your VRAM situation? That changes the answer significantly."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":654,"cacheRead":28719,"cacheWrite":32562,"totalTokens":61978,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774139478778}}
