{"type":"message","id":"86b9cb5e","parentId":"c62848d3","timestamp":"2026-03-22T00:50:30.822Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is great. The Qwen3.5-35B-A3B Uncensored by HauhauCS looks perfect. It's:\n- Qwen3.5 base (excellent quality)\n- 35B MoE (only some parameters active per token, so memory requirements are much lower)\n- Fully uncensored (0/465 refusals)\n- Has BF16 at 65GB (too big) but Q4_K_M at 20GB (fits in A5000!)\n- Also IQ4_XS at 18GB (fits comfortably)\n\nWait, I need to understand the A3B designation. \n\nSo the A3B variant is an MoE model where only 3 billion parameters are active per token out of 35 billion total, which means it runs at roughly 3B inference cost while benefiting from the full 35B parameter capacity for quality. That tracks with Qwen3.5's architecture, and the VRAM requirements confirm this makes sense for the A5000.\n\nFor vLLM deployment on Gradient, I'd need to think about the checkpoint download—either pulling the full 35B model or just the quantized files directly to the instance.\n\nLooking at the actual specs more carefully: Qwen3.5-35B-A3B uses an MoE architecture where only about 3B parameters are active per forward pass, even though the total model size is 35B. In BF16 that would need ~65GB, but with IQ4_XS quantization it drops to ~18GB, which is tight but workable on the A5000's 30GB VRAM with some headroom.\n\nThe model description is key here—\"35B\" likely refers to the total parameter count with 3B active per token, which is a common MoE setup. I should verify what the 35B designation actually means for VRAM requirements, but the Q4_K_M variant at 20GB would give comfortable headroom on the A5000. Let me also look at what else is available in the uncensored model landscape to compare.","thinkingSignature":"f9752f763786c799654dbc4ca49571f952c1c1e23d360631d8b32cff1cbd1d2e"},{"type":"text","text":"\nFound one. Let me look at a couple more options to make a real choice.\n"},{"