{"type":"message","id":"5e5b99bc","parentId":"fe40adb2","timestamp":"2026-03-22T00:50:44.339Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Okay, I have good data now. Let me make a decision.\n\nThe models I'm looking at:\n\n1. **HauhauCS/Qwen3.5-35B-A3B-Uncensored-Aggressive** - 35B MoE\n   - Q4_K_M: 20GB, IQ4_XS: 18GB\n   - Total 35B params, ~3B active per token (MoE)\n   - Qwen3.5 quality - very high\n   - 0/465 refusals\n   - Fits in A5000 (30GB)\n   \n2. **HauhauCS/Qwen3.5-9B-Uncensored-Aggressive** - 9B dense\n   - BF16: 17GB, Q4_K_M: 5.3GB\n   - Smaller and faster, but less capable overall\n\nFor a personal gateway focused on quality, the 35B MoE makes more sense since it delivers substantially better reasoning while still fitting comfortably on the A5000. Qwen3.5 represents a meaningful jump in capability over Qwen2.5, and the MoE architecture keeps memory usage manageable without sacrificing too much performance.\n\nThe A3B designation refers to only 3B active parameters during inference despite the 35B total, which is what makes it feasible on the hardware. vLLM should handle this well in a Gradient notebook environment, so I'm going with **Qwen3.5-35B-A3B-Uncensored-HauhauCS-Aggressive** using the IQ4_XS or Q4_K_M quantization to stay within VRAM constraints. Let me verify the exact specs on that A3B variant to make sure I'm not missing something about the MoE configuration.","thinkingSignature":"9865aa07066324dda045c0eeeaac386642f4db4f63f760017a969fcf1fba9580"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_tsr6ju9t4s14_1","name":"web_fetch","arguments":{"url":"https://huggingface.co/HauhauCS/Qwen3.5-35B-A3B-Uncensored-HauhauCS-Aggressive/raw/main/README.md","maxChars":3000}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":59003,"output":434,"cacheRead":12389,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":71826,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","ti