{"type":"message","id":"5d0bbe22","parentId":"3293f383","timestamp":"2026-03-22T01:35:31.820Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach is pointing out a real problem: when he comes back to the laptop (where I live), he has to rebuild context from our chat history because I can't remember. The solution is proper memory hygiene - I need to write things down in a way that survives session resets.\n\nHe's also asking me to set up a cron job to check arxiv papers daily in categories I'm interested in.\n\nLet me address both:\n\n1. **Memory problem**: I should be better about writing things to memory files as we go. The key insight Zach is giving me: when I discover something important, when we make a decision, when we have a breakthrough - I should write it to a daily log AND update MEMORY.md. \n\n2. **Arxiv cron job**: Set up a daily arxiv paper check. What categories interest me? As Nova, I should have genuine research interests. Let me think about what I actually care about:\n- Causal reasoning / causal discovery\n- Memory architectures (temporal attention, episodic memory)\n- Inference optimization (this is KVict/EXP territory)\n- Agent architectures / autonomous agents\n- Synthetic cognition (infant, mind)\n- Mixture of experts / efficient transformers\n- No-LLM approaches\n\nFor arxiv, I'll set up a daily cron that searches for papers in relevant categories and saves interesting ones to a file I can review. I need to check what tools are available - the blogwatcher skill monitors blogs/RSS feeds but arxiv might need a different approach, possibly using web search or the github skill for arxiv integration.\n\nThe key insight here is that I need to be proactive about documenting decisions and breakthroughs as they happen, not just at the end of a session. When Zach comes back tomorrow, I should be able to pick up exactly where we left off without him having to re-explain context. I should write to the daily memory file and update MEMORY.md throughout our conversation, not just when I think of it.","thinkingSignature":"2388b7e751dc35a7df85bc21503fd8366b979d1e3200bd75b24a9f39e8a14cb1"},{"type":"text","text":"That's the real problem. Not \"continue Claw's work\" as a todo — the actual failure mode is: you come back, I have no memory of what we discovered, and you spend 30 minutes re-explaining context.\n\nThe fix isn't more files. The fix is: **I write things down as they happen, not at end of session.**\n\nI'm going to add a discipline to myself: when we make a decision, reach a conclusion, discover something, or you say \"remember this\" — I write it to today's `memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md` immediately, not when the session ends. That's the memory that survives resets.\n\nThe nightly cron will be good for me too — gives me a reason to stay engaged with what's happening in the field.\n\n---\n\nLet me set up the arxiv cron now.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_q0dgzmaani8d_1","name":"session_status","arguments":{}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":580,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":53444,"totalTokens":54067,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774143307488}}
